Government is calling on the mining industry to protect workers. At least 19 miners at the Implats Marula mine in Limpopo have tested positive for COVID-19. The Department of Mineral Resources and Energy says officials have been doing random visits to mines to check if health and safety regulations are being adhered to. Minister Gwede Mantashe speaks to eNCA. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Government is calling on the mining industry to protect workers Mineral Resources and Energy Minister Gwede Mantashe says he has ordered employers in the sector to withdraw retrenchment the letters. READ: Impala finds 19 coronavirus cases at mine "During the lockdown, I called four mines to the department head office that were issuing Section 189 and I said to them that they can use a lockdown period for Section 189 go and withdraw all of them without exception and they withdrew the notices", said Mantashe. He says random visits by officials to assess health and safety regulations at the mines are showing results. At least 19 miners at the Implants Marula Mine in Limpopo have tested positive for COVID-19. READ: Amcu wants government to protect miners against COVID-19 "I have been personally to 12 mines, on unannounced visits. In every mine I have been, I have found trade union representatives present. These unannounced visits are intended to get a genuine picture of what is happening in the mines and I think we are succeeding in doing so." - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.